Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for your `BackgroundProcessor`.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | **Cancellable work loop** — force-stop a processing thread |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Control flow** — cleanup on forced abort |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Continue execution** — keep thread alive for `finally` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `GetNextItem()` blocks | **Blocking call interruption** — abort can't wake it in .NET 8 |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; no ResetAbort needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time — it's stuck in uncooperative code.
            // Log a warning; you cannot force-kill a managed thread in .NET 8.
            Console.WriteLine("Warning: worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — just exit the loop normally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for thread exit instead of hoping |

## Critical: Update `GetNextItem`

Your `GetNextItem()` **blocks** — this is the biggest pitfall. Without passing the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it and `Stop()` will hang:

```csharp
// If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // wakes immediately on cancel
}

// If using a manual wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace: _signal.WaitOne();
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Forgetting to thread the token through blocking calls** — cancellation only works if the blocked code checks it. Every blocking method in the chain must accept the token.
2. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaks timers/callbacks. Implement `IDisposable`.
3. **Expecting instant cancellation** — cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints. If `ProcessItem` does heavy work, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at intervals inside it.
4. **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones.
5. **No fallback for truly stuck threads** — if `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that blocks forever, the only .NET 8 escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and using `Process.Kill()`.
